To achieve the effect you want, we can use JavaScript to control the display of the headings and the typing of the text. This code sets a timer to display each heading, then types out the text below each heading, and moves on to the next heading. Each section flashes on screen, followed by the typed-out details.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
<title>Ryan Matthew Pfister - AI LLM Generative Specialist, Prompt Engineer, and More</title>
<style>
    body {
        margin: 0;
        padding: 0;
        background-color: #000;
        color: #0f0;
        font-family: 'Courier New', Courier, monospace;
        overflow: hidden;
    }
    #header {
        margin: 2% 5%;
        font-size: 2em;
    }
    #terminal {
        white-space: pre;
        margin: 0 5%;
        font-size: 1.2em;
    }
</style>
</head>
<body>
<div id="header">Ryan Matthew Pfister: AI LLM Generative Specialist | Prompt Engineer | And More</div>
<div id="terminal"></div>

<script>
    const terminal = document.getElementById('terminal');
    const headings = ["Current Endeavors (December 2021 - Present):", "Work Experience:", "Education:", "Contact:"];
    const details = [
        `...`,
        `1. Ivy Tech Community College, Terre Haute, IN (August 2018 to December 2021)
...`,
        `...`,
        `Email - web3radio@icloud.com | Phone - (812) 974-2634`
    ];

    let sectionIndex = 0;
    let charIndex = 0;

    function flashHeading() {
        terminal.textContent += '\n' + headings[sectionIndex] + '\n';
        setTimeout(typeDetails, 2000);  // wait 2 seconds before typing details
    }

    function typeDetails() {
        const interval = setInterval(() => {
            terminal.textContent += details[sectionIndex][charIndex];
            charIndex++;
            if (charIndex === details[sectionIndex].length) {
                clearInterval(interval);
                charIndex = 0;
                sectionIndex++;
                if (sectionIndex < headings.length) {
                    flashHeading();
                }
            }
        }, 30);  // Faster typing animation
    }

    flashHeading();
</script>
</body>
</html>
```

In this code:
1. The `headings` array contains the headings for each section.
2. The `details` array contains the text for each section.
3. The `flashHeading` function displays a heading from the `headings` array.
4. The `typeDetails` function types out the text for the current section from the `details` array.
5. When the text for a section is done typing, it checks if there are more sections, and if so, it displays the next heading and types out the next section of text.

Now, each section heading will flash on screen, followed by the text for that section being typed out.

